  <p>
    Now, try moving the total ballots cast slider to the end, 14 million. Now, move the margin of victory slider to 11%. Finally, move the traditional audit percentage to 3. Congratulations! This represents the 2008 Presidential race in California, where Barack Obama won 61% of the 13.7 million votes cast. A risk limiting audit would need to check just 97 ballots to have 90% confidence that the given result is not wrong. Meanwhile, California law at the time required significantly more ballots to check -- 137,000, or 1% of the 13,700,000 total ballots cast. WIth significantly fewer ballots to check, election officials can spend their resources auditing other races further down the ballot and upgrading voting equipment.
